Gauteng Health MEC Bandile Masuku, says the department is also struggling with a shortage of nurses. JOHANNESBURG - Overcrowding is being blamed for the deaths of ten infants at Tembisa Hospital. Gauteng Health MEC Bandile Masuku, says the department is also struggling with a shortage of nurses. READ:Â CRE outbreak at Tembisa Hospital kills 10 babies Ten babies died during an antibiotic-resistant bacteria outbreak between November and December last year. Masuku says the bacteria spreads faster when the area is overcrowded. "It's a general problem we have in our country and across the province. Because of overcrowding and staff shortage, we face a situation where one nurse would have looked after more than two babies," said Masuku.